fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2Mitch: 

OK - the initial question is   "How good do I have to be to pass a takeout double?"
The rule first appeared in a book by Ron Klinger.. it works like this
After a takeout double: 

Part 1: Add the number of trumps in your hand to the number of tricks declarer is contracting for.
^*BIf that total is less than 12, you should not convert the double to penalty^*N|cp|2|at|
+
Part 2: If you met the rule of 12, then add the number of trump tricks you expect to win to the number of tricks your opponent is contracting for. 
^*BIf that is at least 10, then you may convert the double to penalty.^*N|cp|2|at|

The rules of 10 and 12 say: 
"Only if you meet ^*Uboth^*N|cp|2|at| of these conditions is your hand strong enough to convert a takeout double to penalty"

Example:   1@s    X     pass     ??    What do you do with each of these hands?

A) @sQxxxx  @hQxx  @dKx  @cxxx        B) @sAKx  @hxx  @dQxxx  @cxxxx 

With A) 
You have 5 spades, so you meet the rule of 12 (5+7=12)
But you cannot be sure of more than 2 trumps, so you add 7+2 = 9 => time to bail out
Bid 1NT

With B) 
You do not meet the rule of 12. 
Bid 1NT                                                                                  ^$40|
